azon.com.au/dp/B07KHLF4P6|website=Amazon|publisher=Nickelodeon|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[DVD Region Code|Region 4]]: September 25, 2019<ref>{{cite web|title=Flight of the Zahracorns \u2502 DVD (Region 4)|ASIN=B07TD43QBP|date=25 September 2019|URL=https://www.amazon.com.au/dp/B07TD43QBP|website=Amazon|publisher=Universal Sony Pictures Entertainment|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>https://www.jbhifi.com.au/products/shimmer-shine-flight-of-the-zahracorns-2019-dvd</ref><ref>https://www.sanity.com.au/products/2428971</ref>\n|-\n| Legend of the Dragon Treasure\n|\n* \"Legend of the Dragon Gem\"\n* \"The Dragon Rider\"\n* \"Zahracorns On Parade\"\n* \"Nazboo\u2019s Magic Robe\"\n* \"Dragon Tales\"\n* \"Nazboo\u2019s Family Reunion\"\n| \n* [[DVD Region Code|Region 1]]: August 20, 2019<ref>{{cite web|title=Legend of the Dragon Treasure \u2502 DVD (Region 1)|ASIN=B07SLGWX79|date=20 August 2019|URL=https://www.amazon.com.au/dp/B07SLGWX79|website=Amazon|publisher=Nickelodeon|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[DVD Region Code|Region 4]]: June 17, 2020<ref>{{cite web|title=Legend of the Dragon Treasure \u2502 DVD (Region 4)|ASIN=B084DFZKH5|date=17 June 2020|URL=https://www.amazon.com.au/dp/B084DFZKH5|website=Amazon|publisher=Paramount|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>https://www.sanity.com.au/products/2465953</ref> [Scheduled]\n|-\n| Journey to Zahramay Oceanea\n|\n* \"Journey to Zahramay Oceanea\"\n* \"The Sea Enchantress\"\n* \"Dance of the Jellyfish\"\n* \"Zeashell Surprise\"\n* \"The Zahramay Zuffer-Puff\"\n* \"Zeacorn Cove\"\n* \"Lights of Oceanea\"\n|\n* [[DVD Region Code|Region 1]]: January 22, 2020\n|}\n\nA Nick Jr. compilation DVD, entitled ''Nickelodeon Favorites: Whiskers & Paws'', was released on January 26, 2016 and consists the episode \"Abraca-Genie\", along with select episodes of ''[[PAW Patrol]]'', ''[[Dora and Friends: Into the City!]]'', ''[[Fresh Beat Band of Spies]]'', ''[[Bubble Guppies]]'', and ''[[Blue's Clues]]''. Another Nick Jr. compilation DVD, entitled Nickelodeon Favorites: A Very Nick Jr. Christmas, was released on October 11, 2016, and consists the episode \"Santa's Little Genies\", along with select episodes of ''[[Blaze and the Monster Machines]]'', ''[[Wallykazam]]'', ''[[Dora and Friends: Into the City]]'', and ''[[Bubble Guppies]]''.<ref>https://www.amazon.com/dp/B014R6Q02E</ref>\n\n===Toys===\nNickelodeon and [[Fisher-Price]] released a toy line based on the show. [[Mega Bloks]] playlets based on the show have been released.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|tt4494948}}\n* [http://www.nickjr.com/shimmer-and-shine/ ''Shimmer and Shine'' on NickJr.com] \n* [http://nickanimationstudio.com/shimmer-and-shine ''Shimmer and Shine'' at NickAnimationStudio.com]\n\n{{Nickelodeon original series}}\n\n<!--categories about the show-->\n\n[[Category:2010s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2015 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated supernatural television series]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:American flash animated television series]]\n[[Category:Nick Jr. original programming]]\n[[Category:Nickelodeon shows]]\n[[Category:Treehouse TV shows]]\n[[Category:Preschool education television series]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n<!--categories about titular characters-->\n[[Category:Children's television characters]]\n[[Category:Fantasy television characters]]\n[[Category:Female characters in animation]]\n[[Category:Fictional anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who can teleport]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who use magic]]\n[[Category:Fictional genies]]\n[[Category:Fictional goddesses]]\n[[Category:Fictional telekinetics]]\n[[Category:Folklore characters]]\n[[Category:Genies in television]]\n[[Category:Television duos]]\n[[Category:Television sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Magical girl television series]]\n", "name_user": "SMargan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDVDs:This is a small typo correction concerning my previous reformatting of the inline citations in the DVD release table. The reference to \"Playful Pets of Zahramay Falls (Region 4), was written as (Region 2) instead of (Region 4).", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shimmer_and_Shine"}
{"title_page": "Mickey Kantor", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Mickey Kantor\n|image        = MichaelKantor.jpg\n|office       = 31st [[United States Secretary of Commerce]]\n|president    = [[Bill Clinton]]\n|term_start   = April 12, 1996\n|term_end     = January 21, 1997\n|predecessor  = [[Ron Brown]]\n|successor    = [[William M. Daley|Bill Daley]]\n|office1      = 11th [[Office of the United States Trade Representative|United States Trade Representative]]\n|president1   = [[Bill Clinton]]\n|term_start1  = January 22, 1993\n|term_end1    = April 12, 1996\n|predecessor1 = [[Carla Anderson Hills|Carla Hills]]\n|successor1   = [[Charlene Barshefsky]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1939|8|7}}\n|birth_place  = [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[Tennessee]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Valerie Woods||1978|end=d}}<br>{{marriage|Heidi Schulman|1982}}\n|children     = 4\n|education    = [[Vanderbilt University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Georgetown University]] {{small|([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n}}\n\n'''Michael Kantor''' (born August 7, 1939) is an American politician and lawyer. After serving as the [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]]-[[Al Gore|Gore]] campaign chair in [[U.S. presidential election, 1992|1992]], Kantor was appointed [[United States Trade Representative]], holding that office from 1993 to 1996. He was, in 1996 and 1997, [[United States Secretary of Commerce]].\n\n==Life and career==\nBorn in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], he holds a B.A. in business and economics from [[Vanderbilt University]], earned in 1961. He then served four years as an officer in the [[United States Navy]] and subsequently earned a J.D. from [[Georgetown University]] in 1968. Initially, Kantor worked for the [[Legal Services Corporation]], providing legal assistance to migrant farm workers. From 1976-1993, he practiced law with the Los Angeles law firm of Manatt, Phelps, Phillips & Kantor (now [[Manatt, Phelps & Phillips LLP]]), and was active in Democratic politics and fundraising. He formerly served and is founder of the LA Conservation Corps<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lacorps.org/about/history-founder/|title=LA Conservation Corps \u00bb History & Founder|last=|first=|date=|website=|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref>.\n\nAn advocate of [[free trade]], Kantor, as Trade Representative, led U.S. negotiations that created the [[World Trade Organization]] (WTO), such as the [[Uruguay Round]], and [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] (NAFTA). Kantor also engaged in organizing the [[Miami Summit of the Americas]] and three meetings of the [[Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation]], including the U.S.-hosted First Leaders' Meeting. With the [[European Commission]] of the newly formed European Union, he expanded the trans-Atlantic market.\n\nKantor practices law in the Los Angeles office of [[Mayer Brown]],<ref name=\"mayerbrown.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mayerbrown.com/people/Michael-Kantor/|title=Michael  Kantor - People - Mayer Brown|publisher=|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref> an international law firm based in Chicago. Currently, he is the Board of Directors Co-Chair of Vision to Learn<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://visiontolearn.org/about/leadership/|title=Leadership|last=|first=|date=2020-02-19|website=www.visiontolearn.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and the [[University of Southern California]] [[Annenberg Center on Communication Leadership & Policy]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://communicationleadership.usc.edu/about/advisory-board/|title=Advisory Board {{!}} USC Annenberg Center on Communication Leadership & Policy|website=communicationleadership.usc.edu|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> a Board officer of [[Drug Strategies]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.drugstrategies.com/home/board-of-directors/michael-kantor/|title=Michael Kantor|date=2014-04-13|work=Drug Strategies|access-date=2020-02-19|language=en-US}}</ref> a Leadership Council member of the [[Sargent Shriver]] Center on Poverty Law;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.povertylaw.org/about-us/board-departments/|title=Boards and Councils|website=Shriver Center on Poverty Law|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> a Steering Committee member of Japan House;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.japanhouse.jp/losangeles/aboutus/index.html|title=The Global Japan House Project|website=JAPAN HOUSE(Los Angeles)|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> and a Board member of [[Lexmark|Lexmark International, Inc.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lexmark.com/en_us/about/company/board-of-directors.html|title=Board of Directors|website=www.lexmark.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> and the [[Pacific Council on International Policy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pacificcouncil.org/about/leadership/board|title=Leadership|date=2020-02-19|website=|publisher=Pacific Council on International Policy|url-status=live|archivedate=|accessdate=}}</ref>  \n\nHe formerly served on the Board of Directors of [[CBRE Group|CBRE]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ir.cbre.com/leadership/board-of-directors/default.aspx|title=CBRE Group, Inc. - Leadership - Board of Directors|website=ir.cbre.com|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> Board of Visitors for [[Georgetown University Law Center|Georgetown Law]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.georgetown.edu/alumni/alumni-leadership/board-of-visitors/members/|title=Members of the Board of Visitors|website=www.law.georgetown.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> and International Advisory Board for [[FleishmanHillard]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fleishmanhillard.com/about/iab/|title=International Advisory Board {{!}} FleishmanHillard|last=|first=|date=|website=FleishmanHillard|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> \n\nKantor has been married to broadcast journalist Heidi Schulman since 1982, following the death of his first wife, Valerie Woods Kantor in a 1978 [[PSA Flight 182|plane crash]] in [[San Diego]].<ref>\"In Memoriam.\" ''From The Classes''. Sarah Lawrence College, Bronxville, NY. March, 1979. p. 30.</ref><ref name=\"LA Times\"/> He has children Leslie, Douglas (from the first marriage), and Alix (from the second marriage); and grandchildren Ryan, Jackson, and Zack. Another son by Valerie, Russell, died in a single-car crash in October, 1988, while a senior in high school.<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1988-10-30-me-907-story.html |title=Son of Activist Kantor, 3 Others Killed in Crash |last= |first= |date=30 October 1988 |website= |publisher=Los Angeles Times |access-date= |quote=}}.</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Hi! Please visit WP:BLP and read BEFORE adding links to, say, videos that came from Digg or Slashdot. Non-neutral info will be deleted and the editor possibly blocked for knowingly adding vandalism. Thanks. -->\n*{{C-SPAN|Mickey Kantor}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Carla Anderson Hills|Carla Hills]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Office of the United States Trade Representative|United States Trade Representative]]|years=1993\u20131996}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Charlene Barshefsky]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ron Brown]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of Commerce]]|years=1996\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William M. Daley|Bill Daley]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{USSecCommerce}}\n{{USTR}}\n{{Clinton cabinet}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kantor, Mickey}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Clinton administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American corporate directors]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University Law Center alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Democrats]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:United States Secretaries of Commerce]]\n[[Category:United States Trade Representatives]]\n[[Category:Vanderbilt University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Mickey Kantor\n|image        = MichaelKantor.jpg\n|office       = 31st [[United States Secretary of Commerce]]\n|president    = [[Bill Clinton]]\n|term_start   = April 12, 1996\n|term_end     = January 21, 1997\n|predecessor  = [[Ron Brown (U.S. politician)|Ron Brown]]\n|successor    = [[William M. Daley|Bill Daley]]\n|office1      = 11th [[Office of the United States Trade Representative|United States Trade Representative]]\n|president1   = [[Bill Clinton]]\n|term_start1  = January 22, 1993\n|term_end1    = April 12, 1996\n|predecessor1 = [[Carla Anderson Hills|Carla Hills]]\n|successor1   = [[Charlene Barshefsky]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1939|8|7}}\n|birth_place  = [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[Tennessee]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Valerie Woods||1978|end=d}}<br>{{marriage|Heidi Schulman|1982}}\n|children     = 4\n|education    = [[Vanderbilt University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Georgetown University]] {{small|([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n}}\n\n'''Michael Kantor''' (born August 7, 1939) is an American politician and lawyer. After serving as the [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]]-[[Al Gore|Gore]] campaign chair in [[U.S. presidential election, 1992|1992]], Kantor was appointed [[United States Trade Representative]], holding that office from 1993 to 1996. He was, in 1996 and 1997, [[United States Secretary of Commerce]].\n\n==Life and career==\nBorn in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], he holds a B.A. in business and economics from [[Vanderbilt University]], earned in 1961. He then served four years as an officer in the [[United States Navy]] and subsequently earned a J.D. from [[Georgetown University]] in 1968. Initially, Kantor worked for the [[Legal Services Corporation]], providing legal assistance to migrant farm workers. From 1976-1993, he practiced law with the Los Angeles law firm of Manatt, Phelps, Phillips & Kantor (now [[Manatt, Phelps & Phillips LLP]]), and was active in Democratic politics and fundraising. He formerly served and is founder of the LA Conservation Corps<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lacorps.org/about/history-founder/|title=LA Conservation Corps \u00bb History & Founder|last=|first=|date=|website=|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref>.\n\nAn advocate of [[free trade]], Kantor, as Trade Representative, led U.S. negotiations that created the [[World Trade Organization]] (WTO), such as the [[Uruguay Round]], and [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] (NAFTA). Kantor also engaged in organizing the [[Miami Summit of the Americas]] and three meetings of the [[Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation]], including the U.S.-hosted First Leaders' Meeting. With the [[European Commission]] of the newly formed European Union, he expanded the trans-Atlantic market.\n\nKantor practices law in the Los Angeles office of [[Mayer Brown]],<ref name=\"mayerbrown.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mayerbrown.com/people/Michael-Kantor/|title=Michael  Kantor - People - Mayer Brown|publisher=|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref> an international law firm based in Chicago. Currently, he is the Board of Directors Co-Chair of Vision to Learn<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://visiontolearn.org/about/leadership/|title=Leadership|last=|first=|date=2020-02-19|website=www.visiontolearn.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and the [[University of Southern California]] [[Annenberg Center on Communication Leadership & Policy]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://communicationleadership.usc.edu/about/advisory-board/|title=Advisory Board {{!}} USC Annenberg Center on Communication Leadership & Policy|website=communicationleadership.usc.edu|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> a Board officer of [[Drug Strategies]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.drugstrategies.com/home/board-of-directors/michael-kantor/|title=Michael Kantor|date=2014-04-13|work=Drug Strategies|access-date=2020-02-19|language=en-US}}</ref> a Leadership Council member of the [[Sargent Shriver]] Center on Poverty Law;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.povertylaw.org/about-us/board-departments/|title=Boards and Councils|website=Shriver Center on Poverty Law|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> a Steering Committee member of Japan House;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.japanhouse.jp/losangeles/aboutus/index.html|title=The Global Japan House Project|website=JAPAN HOUSE(Los Angeles)|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> and a Board member of [[Lexmark|Lexmark International, Inc.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lexmark.com/en_us/about/company/board-of-directors.html|title=Board of Directors|website=www.lexmark.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> and the [[Pacific Council on International Policy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pacificcouncil.org/about/leadership/board|title=Leadership|date=2020-02-19|website=|publisher=Pacific Council on International Policy|url-status=live|archivedate=|accessdate=}}</ref>  \n\nHe formerly served on the Board of Directors of [[CBRE Group|CBRE]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ir.cbre.com/leadership/board-of-directors/default.aspx|title=CBRE Group, Inc. - Leadership - Board of Directors|website=ir.cbre.com|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> Board of Visitors for [[Georgetown University Law Center|Georgetown Law]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.georgetown.edu/alumni/alumni-leadership/board-of-visitors/members/|title=Members of the Board of Visitors|website=www.law.georgetown.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> and International Advisory Board for [[FleishmanHillard]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fleishmanhillard.com/about/iab/|title=International Advisory Board {{!}} FleishmanHillard|last=|first=|date=|website=FleishmanHillard|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref> \n\nKantor has been married to broadcast journalist Heidi Schulman since 1982, following the death of his first wife, Valerie Woods Kantor in a 1978 [[PSA Flight 182|plane crash]] in [[San Diego]].<ref>\"In Memoriam.\" ''From The Classes''. Sarah Lawrence College, Bronxville, NY. March, 1979. p. 30.</ref><ref name=\"LA Times\"/> He has children Leslie, Douglas (from the first marriage), and Alix (from the second marriage); and grandchildren Ryan, Jackson, and Zack. Another son by Valerie, Russell, died in a single-car crash in October, 1988, while a senior in high school.<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1988-10-30-me-907-story.html |title=Son of Activist Kantor, 3 Others Killed in Crash |last= |first= |date=30 October 1988 |website= |publisher=Los Angeles Times |access-date= |quote=}}.</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Hi! Please visit WP:BLP and read BEFORE adding links to, say, videos that came from Digg or Slashdot. Non-neutral info will be deleted and the editor possibly blocked for knowingly adding vandalism. Thanks. -->\n*{{C-SPAN|Mickey Kantor}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Carla Anderson Hills|Carla Hills]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Office of the United States Trade Representative|United States Trade Representative]]|years=1993\u20131996}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Charlene Barshefsky]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ron Brown (U.S. politician)|Ron Brown]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of Commerce]]|years=1996\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William M. Daley|Bill Daley]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{USSecCommerce}}\n{{USTR}}\n{{Clinton cabinet}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kantor, Mickey}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Clinton administration cabinet members]]\n[[